nI think it's best to assert that the call returns true and that the collected methods include both names. This approach still triggers the internal getMethods call and exercises that code path, which seems beneficial. The user mentioned not using reflection directly unless the public API demands it, but I wonder if our use of MethodHandles to call package-private or private methods could be a violation. \\n\\nIt might be necessary for class coverage, but I’ll consider whether we can avoid direct invocation altogether and explore using the SecurityManager to trigger this through a higher-level API instead.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining method visibility**\\n\\nOur previous search didn't reveal any direct references outside of MethodUtil, which raises a question about whether getPublicMethods is actually public. I wonder if we might be able to call it through other JavaFX public APIs under the SecurityManager, but that feels indirect and somewhat tricky. The user's task focuses on active classes, and we aim to avoid reflection unless absolutely necessary. \\n\\nYet, I’m uncertain if there's any public API utilizing MethodUtil.getPublicMethods. I found that only MethodHelper has references to MethodUtil.invoke. It seems that getPublicMethods may only be accessed through those package-private APIs within other components. I should think more about this.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating method access**\\n\\nI need to consider that existing tests may have passed without additional metadata because they didn't reflect directly on tests. With our new approach using MethodHandles, we might require metadata to access library methods appropriately. The compilation may not be aware of the target without reflection configuration. Native images typically need metadata, which can be risky. Alternatively, we could leverage Java reflection on the test class rather than the library. It's crucial to inspect build reports from previous runs, as we can't rely solely on them now.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing method accessibility**\\n\\nI just realized that `getPublicMethods` is package-private static, and `getInternalPublicMethods` is private static. It seems no public entry point actually uses `getPublicMethods`. Maybe some code in internal library classes calls it? I searched the MethodUtil class using `javap/strings` but only found references to MethodUtil and not any callers, which might mean methods are called indirectly via `invokedynamic`. \\n\\nTo ensure comprehensive analysis, using `javap -c -p` along with a search for `MethodUtil.getPublicMethods` across relevant classes could help, but my search timed out. It’s possible that limiting to the `com.sun.javafx.property` package might yield better results. Ultimately, to cover reflections, the only way seems to be using `MethodUtil.class.getDeclaredMethod()`, even though direct reflection is discouraged.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering native image metadata**\\n\\nI'm realizing that native image metadata might still present an issue. Even though `findStatic` references a private method, it could require metadata as well. However, method handles generated with constant method names may not need reflect metadata. I think Native Image could perform partial evaluation and might handle constant MethodHandles lookup if given the right class and method strings.\\n\\nIt's a bit unclear, so I might need to adjust my assertions. Perhaps making the package-private base class public could help, especially if we want to avoid issues with `getInternalPublicMethods`.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_dVAhXQcOCwnFELqenJOoatQU|fc_0c59f6ae114282ef0169f0a65bdb8c8193b69328eca5602a56", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.openjfx/javafx-base/13-ea/src/test/java/org_openjfx/javafx_base/MethodUtilTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "    void getMethodFindsInheritedPublicMethodsDeclaredOnANonPublicSuperc